// What is OOP?

// Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is a programming paradigm (means a style of writing a code in a another way like functional programming) that uses "objects" & "classes" to design applications and computer programs.

// Why we need OOP?

// Case Study: We want to create a program to manage a library. We need to keep track of books, authors, and borrowers. We also want to hide some information.

// Limitations of Functional Programming / Procedural Programming:

// 1. Code Reusability: In functional programming, we often have to write the same code multiple times for different data types or operations. This can lead to code duplication and maintenance issues.
// 2. Data Encapsulation: In functional programming, data is often exposed and can be modified by any part of the program. This can lead to unintended side effects and bugs.
// 3. Modularity: In functional programming, it can be difficult to organize code into modular components. This can make it harder to manage and understand large codebases.
// 4. Real-world Modeling: Functional programming can struggle to model real-world entities and their interactions effectively, as it focuses on functions rather than objects that represent real-world concepts.

// What problems OOP solves in this case study?

// 1. Code Reusability: OOP allows us to create classes that can be reused across different parts of the program. For example, we can create a "Book" class that can be used to represent all books in the library, and we can create an "Author" class that can be used to represent all authors. This promotes code reusability and reduces duplication.
// 2. Data Encapsulation: OOP allows us to encapsulate data and hide it from other parts of the program. For example, we can make the attributes of the "Book" class private and provide public methods to access and modify them. This helps to prevent unintended side effects and bugs, as the internal state of the object is protected from outside interference.
// 3. Modularity: OOP allows us to organize code into modular components. For example, we can create separate classes for "Book", "Author", and "Borrower". This makes it easier to manage and understand the codebase, as each class has a specific responsibility and can be developed and tested independently.
// 4. Real-world Modeling: OOP allows us to model real-world entities and their interactions effectively. For example, we can create a "Library" class that contains a collection of "Book" objects and a collection of "Author" objects. This allows us to represent the relationships between books, authors, and borrowers in a way that closely mirrors the real world, making it easier to understand and work with the data.

// In summary, OOP provides a powerful way to design and organize code that promotes code reusability, data encapsulation, modularity, and effective modeling of real-world entities. It helps to solve the limitations of functional programming and allows us to create more maintainable and scalable applications.
